<div class='commentinfo comment_comment'>
2014-01-17 07:35:00 (134 days ago)
<div id='contact-155943'><span class='name'>Jonathan Ryan</span><span class='send-message'><a href="/content/Contact/view/contactid/155943/display/detail/">Details</a></span></div> </div>
<div class='commentbox'>
Notes: Do not confuse the Applachia Dam with the Applachia Powerhouse. The Powerhouse is 8.8 miles<br/>
downstream from the dam. It gets its water from the dam via a tunnel. (Hiwassee dam is completely<br/>
different from either of these.) The dam may release water into the river at very high lake levels,<br/>
but it does not generate power, and has no scheduled releases. The Powerhouse is about 1/2 mile<br/>
above the put in, and is where all the water for paddling from the Powerhouse put-in to Reliance<br/>
comes from. (Unless the dam is spilling water.) The USGS river gauge on the Hiwassee is at<br/>
Charleston, below the confluence of the Hiwassee and the Ocoee Rivers, so it cannot be used as a<br/>
reliable indicator of water levels for either river, especially since both are dam controlled. The<br/>
link to TVA Applachia Powerhouse is: http://www.tva.gov/lakes/aph_r.htm TVA has a smartphone app<br/>
that makes it very easy to check all its dam releases. </div>
</td>
</tr>
